Class Mod

  • java.lang.Object
    • skyproc.Mod
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.lang.Comparable, java.lang.Iterable<GRUP>

    public class Mod
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.lang.Comparable, java.lang.Iterable<GRUP>
    A mod is a collection of GRUPs which contain records. Mods are used to create patches by creating an empty one, adding records, and then calling its export function.

      • makeCopy

        public MajorRecord makeCopy(MajorRecord m,
                   java.lang.String newEDID)
        Makes a copy of the Major Record and loads it into the mod, giving a new Major Record a FormID originating from the mod. This function also automatically adds the new copied record to the mod. This makes two separate records independent of each other.

        COMPILER NOTE: The record returned can only be determined by the compiler to be a Major Record. You must cast it yourself to be the correct type of major record.
        ex. NPC_ newNPC = (NPC_) myPatch.makeCopy(otherNPC);
        Parameters:
        m - Major Record to make a copy of and add to the mod.
        newEDID - EDID to assign to the new record. Make sure it's unique.
        Returns:
        The copied record, or null if either parameter is null.

      • addAsOverrides

        public void addAsOverrides(Mod rhs,
                  GRUP_TYPE... grup_types)
        This function will merge all GRUPs from the rhs mod into the calling mod.
        Any records already in the mod will be overwritten by the version from rhs.

        NOTE: Merging will NOT add records from a mod with a matching ModListing. This is to prevent patches taking in information from old versions of themselves.
        Parameters:
        rhs - Mod whose GRUPs to add in.
        grup_types - Any amount of GRUPs to merge in, separated by commas. Leave this empty if you want all GRUPs merged.

      • addAsOverrides

        public void addAsOverrides(java.util.ArrayList<Mod> in,
                  GRUP_TYPE... grup_types)
        Iterates through each mod in the ArrayList, in order, and merges them in one by one.
        This means any conflicting records within the list will end up with the last mod's version.

        NOTE: Merging will NOT add records from a mod with a matching ModListing. This is to prevent patches taking in information from old versions of themselves.
        Parameters:
        in - ArrayList of mods to merge in.
        grup_types - Any amount of GRUPs to merge in, separated by commas. Leave this empty if you want all GRUPs merged.

      • addAsOverrides

        public void addAsOverrides(java.util.Collection<Mod> in,
                  GRUP_TYPE... grup_types)
        NOTE: To sort the mods in load order, use a TreeSet.
        Iterates through each mod in the Set and merges them in one by one.
        This means any conflicting records within the set will end up with the last mod's version.

        NOTE: Merging will NOT add records from a mod with a matching ModListing. This is to prevent patches taking in information from old versions of themselves.
        Parameters:
        in - Set of mods to merge in.
        grup_types - Any amount of GRUPs to merge in, separated by commas. Leave this empty if you want all GRUPs merged.

      • addAsOverrides

        public void addAsOverrides(SPDatabase db,
                  GRUP_TYPE... grup_types)
        Iterates through each mod in the SPDatabase, in load order, and merges them in one by one.
        This means any conflicting records within the database will end up with the last mod's version.

        NOTE: Merging will NOT add records from a mod with a matching ModListing. This is to prevent patches taking in information from old versions of themselves.
        Parameters:
        db - The SPDatabase to merge in.
        grup_types - Any amount of GRUPs to merge in, separated by commas. Leave this empty if you want all GRUPs merged.

      • export

        public void export()
            throws java.io.IOException,
                   BadRecord
        Exports the mod to the path designated by SPGlobal.pathToData.
        Throws:
        java.io.IOException - If there are any unforseen disk errors exporting the data.
        BadRecord - If duplicate EDIDs are found in the mod. This has been deemed an unacceptable mod format, and is thrown to promote the investigation and elimination of duplicate EDIDs.
        See Also:
        SPGlobal

      • compareTo

        public int compareTo(java.lang.Object o)
        A compare function used for sorting Mods in load order.
        .esp > .esm
        later date > earlier date
        Specified by:
        compareTo in interface java.lang.Comparable
        Parameters:
        o - Another Mod object
        Returns:
        1: Mod is later in the load order
        -1: Mod is earlier in the load order
        0: Mod is equal in load order (should not happen)
